WEBVTT

00:02.085 --> 00:03.160
<i>Tonight on</i>
The Curse of Oak Island...

00:03.253 --> 00:04.911
<i>MARTY:
We're back, Oak Island,</i>

00:04.996 --> 00:05.754
old friend.

00:05.913 --> 00:08.999
Hold it! Whoa, look at that!

00:09.083 --> 00:10.259
(beeping)

00:10.418 --> 00:11.918
- Something in there.
- Oh, there's something in there.

00:12.012 --> 00:14.671
- Yeah, it's a big chunk of metal right there.
- CRAIG: Wow.

00:14.764 --> 00:16.173
<i>IAN:
I'll give it a shot here.</i>

00:16.257 --> 00:18.434
Wow, those are
some strange elements.

00:18.593 --> 00:20.093
- GARY: AU.
- RICK: Really?

00:20.178 --> 00:21.979
That would be gold.

00:23.106 --> 00:25.098
These came back
with one time period.

00:25.191 --> 00:26.183
Really and truthfully?

00:26.267 --> 00:27.359
Medieval, baby!

00:31.105 --> 00:33.940
<i>NARRATOR: There is an
island in the North Atlantic</i>

00:34.025 --> 00:37.277
<i>where people have been looking
for an incredible treasure</i>

00:37.361 --> 00:40.363
<i>for more than 200 years.</i>

00:40.448 --> 00:43.366
<i>So far, they have found
a stone slab</i>

00:43.451 --> 00:45.794
<i>with strange symbols
carved into it,</i>

00:45.879 --> 00:50.549
<i>man-made workings that date
to Medieval times,</i>

00:50.633 --> 00:54.211
<i>and a lead cross
whose origin may be connected</i>

00:54.295 --> 00:55.712
<i>to the Knights Templar.</i>

00:55.805 --> 01:01.143
<i>To date, six men have died
trying to solve the mystery.</i>

01:01.302 --> 01:03.804
<i>And, according to legend,</i>

01:03.888 --> 01:06.723
<i>one more will have to die</i>

01:06.816 --> 01:09.818
<i>before the treasure
can be found.</i>

01:09.903 --> 01:11.904
♪ ♪

01:22.582 --> 01:25.408
TERRY: And the day
begins. Here we go.

01:25.502 --> 01:30.589
<i>NARRATOR: It is the start of a
new day of exploration on Oak Island.</i>

01:30.748 --> 01:34.426
- This is gonna be it, man.
<i>- And for brothers Rick and Marty Lagina and their team,</i>

01:34.511 --> 01:37.838
<i>their level
of excitement and anticipation</i>

01:37.931 --> 01:41.174
<i>of a major discovery
has never been higher.</i>

01:41.267 --> 01:42.843
TERRY:
Okay, it's showtime!

01:42.927 --> 01:44.186
CHARLES:
Here we go.

01:44.345 --> 01:46.596
Now we're cooking with gas.

01:46.689 --> 01:48.265
- STEVE G.: We're on D-2, right?
- Yep.

01:48.349 --> 01:53.112
This is a good hole, because we
have about a 15-foot rectangle

01:53.196 --> 01:55.614
with good data,
but unknown data.

01:55.773 --> 01:57.607
So we're going west to see
how far this extends.

01:57.692 --> 01:59.284
We're gonna continue to chase
this wood

01:59.369 --> 02:00.869
till we no longer find it.

02:01.028 --> 02:03.705
And then we know it lives
in this area.

02:03.790 --> 02:05.031
Yeah.

02:05.116 --> 02:08.034
<i>NARRATOR:
Today they have begun drilling</i>

02:08.128 --> 02:10.871
<i>a new borehole known as D-2,</i>

02:10.955 --> 02:13.549
<i>which is located less than
eight feet from the C-1 Shaft</i>

02:13.708 --> 02:15.968
<i>in the Money Pit.</i>

02:16.052 --> 02:18.712
<i>The team has dubbed the area
the "C-1 Cluster,"</i>

02:18.805 --> 02:21.557
<i>not only because they have
recently discovered evidence</i>

02:21.641 --> 02:24.968
<i>of a man-made tunnel system
some 90 feet deep,</i>

02:25.061 --> 02:27.646
<i>but also,
evidence of the treasure</i>

02:27.805 --> 02:31.975
<i>people have been looking for
since 1795.</i>

02:32.068 --> 02:33.569
So, what have you got
to tell us?

02:33.728 --> 02:35.729
<i>NARRATOR:
One week ago,</i>

02:35.822 --> 02:39.658
<i>geoscientists Dr. Ian Spooner
and Dr. Peir Pufahl</i>

02:39.817 --> 02:41.994
<i>presented their astonishing
report of water samples</i>

02:42.153 --> 02:44.746
<i>taken in previously drilled
boreholes</i>

02:44.906 --> 02:47.157
<i>in the area of the C-1 Cluster.</i>

02:47.241 --> 02:49.743
Here's the bottom line:
it's got gold in it.

02:49.836 --> 02:51.328
<i>It's got gold in the water,</i>

02:51.421 --> 02:52.996
and if it's got gold
in the water,

02:53.089 --> 02:54.748
the gold is coming
from somewhere.

02:54.832 --> 02:56.082
<i>RICK:
I told you Bravo-Tango</i>

02:56.167 --> 02:57.426
was coming at some point.

02:58.336 --> 03:00.762
Continue on here with the, uh,

03:00.847 --> 03:02.931
- soil sampling to get the background and gold content.
- Yep.

03:03.016 --> 03:04.600
Right.

03:04.759 --> 03:09.512
Dr. Spooner basically looked at
all kinds of different samples,

03:09.597 --> 03:12.858
and his overall conclusion
was that he could not find

03:13.017 --> 03:15.194
a natural source
for the gold and the silver

03:15.278 --> 03:17.196
we're seeing in the water.

03:17.280 --> 03:20.273
(laughs):
There she is! Beautiful!

03:20.358 --> 03:22.776
<i>MARTY:
That is really good news.</i>

03:22.860 --> 03:25.787
<i>Does it absolutely mean
it's coming from a treasure? No.</i>

03:25.872 --> 03:29.208
But does it get us closer
by process of elimination?

03:29.292 --> 03:31.034
Yes, definitely.

03:31.127 --> 03:33.703
<i>NARRATOR:
Now the Oak Island team</i>

03:33.788 --> 03:35.214
<i>is in the process of drilling</i>

03:35.298 --> 03:38.208
<i>up to 20 new boreholes
across a strategic grid,</i>

03:38.301 --> 03:40.710
<i>taking core samples
at ten-foot intervals</i>

03:40.795 --> 03:44.381
<i>down to depths
of as much as 200 feet</i>

03:44.474 --> 03:46.383
<i>in an attempt
to pinpoint the location</i>

03:46.467 --> 03:48.885
<i>of the possible treasure.</i>

03:48.978 --> 03:51.638
<i>Once completed,
they intend to dig</i>

03:51.722 --> 03:54.224
<i>a number of ten-foot-wide
steel-cased shafts</i>

03:54.308 --> 03:57.069
<i>later this year,
and hopefully solve</i>

03:57.228 --> 04:00.313
<i>the Oak Island mystery
once and for all.</i>

04:00.406 --> 04:03.075
<i>RICK: The hope,
certainly, amongst the team</i>

04:03.234 --> 04:05.986
<i>is that they
can reverse-engineer</i>

04:06.079 --> 04:07.404
<i>where these deposits</i>

04:07.488 --> 04:11.408
might be
and put an "X" on the ground

04:11.501 --> 04:13.410
<i>and investigate it
with a drilling program</i>

04:13.494 --> 04:14.836
<i>or a large can.</i>

04:16.422 --> 04:17.256
We're in a good spot.

04:17.340 --> 04:18.832
So this is gonna tell us a lot.

04:18.916 --> 04:21.835
This is the year that everything
seems to be coming together.

04:21.928 --> 04:23.169
TERRY:
Agreed.

04:23.263 --> 04:25.180
<i>NARRATOR: While the
core-drilling operation</i>

04:25.265 --> 04:27.424
<i>in borehole D-2 continues...</i>

04:27.517 --> 04:30.510
RICK:
How far over do you want to go?

04:30.594 --> 04:33.939
- I mean, we got to do this whole area anyway, so...
- To that? Okay.

04:34.098 --> 04:37.183
<i>in the southeast corner
of the swamp,</i>

04:37.277 --> 04:41.521
<i>Rick Lagina, along with
archaeologists Laird Niven</i>

04:41.614 --> 04:43.690
<i>and Miriam Amirault,</i>

04:43.783 --> 04:46.118
<i>as well as heavy equipment
operator Billy Gerhardt,</i>

04:46.202 --> 04:49.863
<i>continue investigating
near the massive stone road,</i>

04:49.947 --> 04:52.282
<i>or possible ship's wharf,</i>

04:52.366 --> 04:55.294
<i>a ship's wharf that
researcher Terry Deveau believes</i>

04:55.453 --> 04:59.039
<i>could be as much
as 500 years old.</i>

04:59.132 --> 05:01.049
This is a type of road

05:01.134 --> 05:04.377
that was built in Europe
in the 1500s.

05:04.462 --> 05:05.879
CHARLES:
Wow.

05:05.963 --> 05:07.047
TERRY D.:
What comes to my mind

05:07.140 --> 05:08.265
is the Portuguese.

05:10.051 --> 05:11.885
BILLY:
We don't know how deep it is.

05:11.978 --> 05:13.562
We may have enough room there.

05:13.646 --> 05:15.638
If we get anything from there,
that's significant.

05:15.723 --> 05:16.982
BILLY:
Yeah.

05:17.066 --> 05:20.235
We did find a ship's piece

05:20.394 --> 05:22.070
- in that lower layer.
- Yeah.

05:24.899 --> 05:26.658
<i>NARRATOR:
One week ago,</i>

05:26.817 --> 05:29.661
<i>just after Terry's
incredible presentation...</i>

05:29.746 --> 05:32.831
RICK: I would bet anything
that's from a ship.

05:32.990 --> 05:35.000
<i>the team discovered
a curious wood artifact</i>

05:35.084 --> 05:38.161
<i>that may have come
from a large sailing vessel.</i>

05:38.254 --> 05:39.412
CRAIG:
This is one right here, too.

05:39.505 --> 05:41.081
GARY: I think we've
found a barrel here.

05:41.174 --> 05:42.248
<i>along with pieces</i>

05:42.342 --> 05:45.510
<i>of potentially ancient
cargo barrels.</i>

05:45.669 --> 05:48.180
We anticipated the southeast
corner of the swamp

05:48.339 --> 05:50.766
would be productive,
and it's not disappointing.

05:50.850 --> 05:53.935
Finding barrel staves,
things that could be from ships,

05:54.020 --> 05:56.188
um, it's looking good.

05:59.183 --> 06:00.776
- Hey, Laird.
- Hey, Craig.

06:00.935 --> 06:03.186
- I'm here to help.
- Okay.

06:03.279 --> 06:05.113
Billy will bring
the bucket up for you

06:05.198 --> 06:07.115
- and just shake it out.
- Okay.

06:07.274 --> 06:08.450
- All right? Okay.
- Sounds great.

06:10.694 --> 06:12.162
♪ ♪

06:13.289 --> 06:14.614
(scraping)

06:14.707 --> 06:16.792
CRAIG:
Got something here.

06:16.876 --> 06:18.710
- LAIRD: Whoa, Bill.
- Yeah.

06:18.869 --> 06:21.046
CRAIG: There's a structure
there, a wooden structure.

06:21.205 --> 06:23.840
Rick, come look
at this structure we found.

06:25.551 --> 06:27.552
<i>NARRATOR:
A wooden structure?</i>

06:27.711 --> 06:30.130
<i>Buried in the southeast corner
of the swamp?</i>

06:30.223 --> 06:33.466
<i>Could it be connected
to the believed stone wharf?</i>

06:33.559 --> 06:37.479
<i>Or might it be another,
completely separate construct?</i>

06:37.638 --> 06:40.723
<i>If so, who built it? When?</i>

06:40.808 --> 06:42.559
<i>And for what purpose?</i>

06:42.643 --> 06:45.478
CRAIG:
All of a sudden, the, uh, muck

06:45.571 --> 06:46.571
fell away from the side.

06:46.730 --> 06:48.731
You can see the boards--
There was, like,

06:48.825 --> 06:50.242
three boards
on top of each other.

06:50.401 --> 06:51.743
Looks like cribbing

06:51.828 --> 06:53.903
- of some sort.
- Is that, uh...

06:53.988 --> 06:56.656
- dimensional lumber?
- LAIRD: Looks to be.

06:56.740 --> 06:58.992
- Well, I don't actually know.
- CRAIG: I'll jump in there

06:59.076 --> 07:00.160
if you want me to, Laird.

07:00.253 --> 07:02.087
Sure, if you want.

07:04.832 --> 07:06.591
LAIRD:
Going in.

07:11.013 --> 07:13.339
Uh, this appears to be
the bottom here.

07:13.424 --> 07:16.935
- That's all one board to there.
- LAIRD: Wow.

07:17.094 --> 07:20.021
- 12-to 16-inch board.
- That's a huge board.

07:20.106 --> 07:21.848
LAIRD:
It's big, isn't it?

07:21.932 --> 07:24.276
I wonder,
did the Restalls supposedly...

07:24.435 --> 07:28.021
think they probed something
and then dug a shaft

07:28.114 --> 07:29.948
down to it, maybe?

07:30.107 --> 07:31.357
Maybe.

07:31.451 --> 07:33.776
They probed looking for the...

07:33.861 --> 07:35.036
Jack Adams box.

07:36.706 --> 07:38.698
<i>NARRATOR:
According to Jack Adams,</i>

07:38.791 --> 07:43.369
<i>who served as a caretaker
on Oak Island during the 1930s,</i>

07:43.463 --> 07:46.965
<i>while probing in the southeast
corner of the swamp,</i>

07:47.124 --> 07:49.801
<i>he made contact
with a large wooden box</i>

07:49.886 --> 07:54.306
<i>that was buried beneath the
brackish water, muck and mud.</i>

07:54.465 --> 07:57.383
<i>Although the box
was never verified or recovered,</i>

07:57.477 --> 08:00.979
<i>years later, Mr. Adams
shared his believed find</i>

08:01.138 --> 08:04.224
<i>with the Restall family,
who spent five years</i>

08:04.317 --> 08:08.978
<i>living on Oak Island
between 1959 and 1965.</i>

08:09.071 --> 08:10.822
Thank you.

08:10.981 --> 08:13.241
<i>In 2013,</i>

08:13.400 --> 08:16.236
<i>Lee Lamb shared the journals of
her late brother, Bobby Restall,</i>

08:16.329 --> 08:20.248
<i>who documented much of
the family's legendary efforts.</i>

08:20.407 --> 08:22.834
There's September 22, 1960.

08:22.993 --> 08:25.411
This is exactly
what we were talking about.

08:25.505 --> 08:28.414
<i>Included was an entry detailing
how Bobby constructed</i>

08:28.508 --> 08:32.511
<i>a wooden platform in the
southeast corner of the swamp</i>

08:32.595 --> 08:36.089
<i>to search for what Jack Adams
believed to be hidden there.</i>

08:36.182 --> 08:38.841
I have pictures of this, Rick.

08:38.935 --> 08:41.269
There's pictures
of them working in the swamp,

08:41.354 --> 08:43.346
<i>like, leaning over the water</i>

08:43.439 --> 08:46.441
<i>and probing
with this big, long pole.</i>

08:46.526 --> 08:48.944
CRAIG:
It comes all the way up to here.

08:49.028 --> 08:51.029
One solid board.

08:51.113 --> 08:53.865
<i>NARRATOR: Is it possible
that this wooden structure</i>

08:54.024 --> 08:56.526
<i>is part of the platform
Bobby Restall built,</i>

08:56.610 --> 08:59.538
<i>attempting to locate
the so-called "mystery box"?</i>

08:59.697 --> 09:03.366
<i>If so, could that mean
that it is still hidden</i>

09:03.450 --> 09:05.952
<i>somewhere in this area?</i>

09:06.036 --> 09:07.546
BILLY: I guess no matter
which way you look at it,

09:07.705 --> 09:09.548
Restalls or not, you know,
they were here,

09:09.707 --> 09:12.041
and somebody knows something
about this corner of the swamp.

09:12.126 --> 09:13.543
CRAIG:
Oh, yeah.

09:13.636 --> 09:14.961
We're chasing the same thing.

09:15.045 --> 09:17.380
RICK: Okay, well, if
everyone's in agreement,

09:17.473 --> 09:19.299
- well, let's keep going.
- All right.

09:19.392 --> 09:21.718
<i>NARRATOR: While Rick
Lagina continues to oversee</i>

09:21.811 --> 09:24.887
<i>the investigation
in the swamp...</i>

09:24.981 --> 09:27.148
CHARLES:
A core coming out.

09:27.233 --> 09:29.067
TERRY:
Looks like, yep.

09:29.226 --> 09:31.570
<i>NARRATOR:
back in the Money Pit area,</i>

09:31.654 --> 09:33.646
<i>the team has just reached
their zone of interest,</i>

09:33.731 --> 09:36.241
<i>around 90 feet deep
in borehole D-2.</i>

09:37.401 --> 09:40.912
- What's the good word, Adam?
- 88.5.

09:41.071 --> 09:42.163
That's good.

09:42.248 --> 09:43.748
Ready, Terry?

09:47.336 --> 09:49.495
- TERRY: This is more like it.
- STEVE G.: Oh, it's full of wood!

09:49.580 --> 09:51.331
- TERRY: Yeah.
- CHARLES: We've got some major wood there.

09:51.415 --> 09:53.416
TERRY:
Wood piled on top of wood.

09:53.500 --> 09:55.835
Some kind of planking
or material on the floor.

09:55.919 --> 09:57.846
STEVE G.:
That's a lot of wood.

09:57.930 --> 09:59.756
Yeah.

09:59.840 --> 10:01.257
<i>NARRATOR:
Planked wood?</i>

10:01.342 --> 10:04.427
<i>Nearly 90 feet deep
in borehole D-2?</i>

10:04.511 --> 10:08.440
<i>One week ago, the team made
a nearly identical discovery</i>

10:08.524 --> 10:12.352
<i>in borehole CD-6
some 15 feet away.</i>

10:12.445 --> 10:15.855
<i>Is it possible they've
encountered the same structure?</i>

10:15.948 --> 10:19.359
<i>And if so, could it be connected
to the silver and gold</i>

10:19.443 --> 10:22.528
<i>they recently detected
in this area?</i>

10:22.613 --> 10:25.457
- Gentlemen. - STEVE G: Hey, Craig.
- TERRY: Hi, Craig.

10:25.541 --> 10:26.708
- How you doing?
- Take a look at this.

10:26.867 --> 10:28.951
It's dark and looks woody.

10:29.036 --> 10:30.462
This is very dark and woody.

10:30.546 --> 10:31.963
CHARLES:
Yeah.

10:32.122 --> 10:34.123
CRAIG: Did you run your,
uh, metal detector over it?

10:34.216 --> 10:35.541
CHARLES:
I'm gonna do that now.

10:35.626 --> 10:37.126
Charles, I'll get you
some wood samples,

10:37.211 --> 10:39.387
- if you want to grab the bags.
- Yeah, I'll get it. Let me run

10:39.472 --> 10:40.388
the pinpointer over it first.

10:40.473 --> 10:41.765
Okay.

10:45.469 --> 10:47.312
(beeping)

10:47.471 --> 10:48.638
Oh, what do we got?

10:48.722 --> 10:50.640
Let me pick the bag up.

10:51.892 --> 10:53.818
- There's something in there.
- Oh, there's something in there.

10:58.816 --> 11:00.575
STEVE G.: It'd be nice
to find an artifact.

11:00.734 --> 11:02.911
<i>NARRATOR: At a depth of
some 90 feet in borehole D-2</i>

11:03.070 --> 11:05.071
<i>in the Money Pit area,</i>

11:05.164 --> 11:08.908
<i>the Oak Island team
has just retrieved a core sample</i>

11:08.992 --> 11:11.836
<i>that not only contains more
evidence of a wooden structure,</i>

11:11.995 --> 11:13.663
<i>but also something
they hope will be</i>

11:13.747 --> 11:17.175
<i>a much more valuable clue.</i>

11:17.259 --> 11:18.510
CHARLES:
There's something in here.

11:18.594 --> 11:20.420
CRAIG: Oh, there it
is, a piece of flat metal.

11:20.504 --> 11:21.680
CHARLES:
Yeah, it looks like it.

11:22.923 --> 11:24.516
There's metal right here.

11:24.675 --> 11:25.925
- (beeping)
- STEVE G.: That's a big chunk.

11:26.018 --> 11:27.686
CHARLES: Yeah, it's a big
chunk of metal right there.

11:27.845 --> 11:28.853
- STEVE G.: That's good.
- TERRY: Wow.

11:28.938 --> 11:31.764
Hey, can you take a quick look
at this?

11:31.857 --> 11:34.600
Do you think that's mud caked
on there? Clay?

11:34.685 --> 11:37.270
Or do you think it might be
cement of some sort?

11:37.354 --> 11:38.697
Mm, actually, okay.

11:41.275 --> 11:43.609
Yeah, on closer inspection,

11:43.694 --> 11:45.111
yeah, that looks
like it might be

11:45.195 --> 11:47.205
a little more solid than mud.

11:47.289 --> 11:49.958
That looks like is has the
possibility of being cement.

11:50.042 --> 11:51.876
<i>NARRATOR:
Possible cement?</i>

11:52.035 --> 11:54.203
<i>Found 90 feet deep
on a piece of metal</i>

11:54.288 --> 11:56.372
<i>in borehole D-2?</i>

11:56.457 --> 12:00.793
<i>But if so, is it simply evidence
of previous searcher activities</i>

12:00.878 --> 12:03.463
<i>in the Money Pit
from the past two centuries?</i>

12:03.556 --> 12:06.141
<i>Or from something
that was done deep underground</i>

12:06.225 --> 12:08.727
<i>on Oak Island much earlier?</i>

12:08.886 --> 12:10.812
What would they be using
the cement for?

12:10.896 --> 12:12.555
What would they be cementing in?

12:12.639 --> 12:14.557
STEVE G.: What's the
history on that, Charles?

12:14.641 --> 12:18.644
In the vault that the Oak Island
Treasure Company found in 1897,

12:18.729 --> 12:21.656
they drilled through
what they believed to be cement.

12:21.741 --> 12:23.575
They actually sent a sample away
to London,

12:23.734 --> 12:25.401
and it came back
with a high probability

12:25.486 --> 12:28.571
that it was man-made cement.

