<i>NARRATOR: When treasure hunters
Frederick Blair and William Chappell</i>

12:31.575 --> 12:34.335
<i>reported drilling
through a cement substance</i>

12:34.495 --> 12:39.174
<i>that encased a seven-foot-tall
wooden vault back in 1897,</i>

12:39.258 --> 12:42.001
<i>they also discovered
the scrap of parchment paper</i>

12:42.085 --> 12:45.421
<i>bearing the letters V-I
as well as shavings of gold</i>

12:45.506 --> 12:48.257
<i>when they retracted
their drill bit.</i>

12:48.342 --> 12:50.927
CHARLES:
Don't break it.

12:51.011 --> 12:52.937
<i>NARRATOR: Since the team
has already obtained evidence</i>

12:53.096 --> 12:55.348
<i>of both silver and gold
in this area,</i>

12:55.432 --> 12:57.850
<i>could they be close
to finally locating</i>

12:57.935 --> 12:59.694
<i>the so-called "Chappell Vault"?</i>

12:59.779 --> 13:02.104
TERRY:
Interesting.

13:02.189 --> 13:04.699
<i>CHARLES: You know, the fact that
we're finding what could be cement</i>

13:04.858 --> 13:06.701
<i>on this piece of metal,</i>

13:06.786 --> 13:08.277
that brings me back to the story

13:08.370 --> 13:10.288
of the Oak Island
Treasure Company

13:10.372 --> 13:11.873
drilling into the vault.

13:11.957 --> 13:15.794
And they actually went through
cement and a very thin metal.

13:15.878 --> 13:18.379
<i>And that's maybe what we're
actually picking up now.</i>

13:18.464 --> 13:21.299
Yeah, this appears
just metal here.

13:21.383 --> 13:23.134
TERRY: It's a little
too thin for drill casing.

13:23.219 --> 13:24.877
I think so, too, yeah.

13:24.970 --> 13:27.213
<i>RICK: These are the first metals
that we have found</i>

13:27.297 --> 13:29.048
<i>of unknown origin</i>

13:29.141 --> 13:30.391
in the Money Pit.

13:30.551 --> 13:31.976
We've recovered metals,

13:32.061 --> 13:34.220
but in association
with drive shoes

13:34.304 --> 13:36.722
and old shafts and nails.

13:36.816 --> 13:39.058
This is a unique find

13:39.142 --> 13:41.569
at a depth we're
significantly interested in,

13:41.654 --> 13:44.823
in a previously unexplored area.

13:44.982 --> 13:46.816
<i>It means you're close
to a structure.</i>

13:46.900 --> 13:49.410
<i>That's my interpretation.</i>

13:49.495 --> 13:51.487
It would be interesting to see
if there is correlation

13:51.572 --> 13:53.331
or relation between the two.
I mean,

13:53.415 --> 13:55.583
- as we know, multiple workings underground.
- Absolutely.

13:55.742 --> 13:59.254
Dr. Brousseau can look at the
metal and see if it's cement.

13:59.413 --> 14:01.923
Okay, let's bag 'er.

14:02.007 --> 14:05.918
- CHARLES: Okay.
<i>- NARRATOR: While drilling in the Money Pit continues,</i>

14:06.011 --> 14:08.004
<i>along with the search
in the southeast corner</i>

14:08.088 --> 14:10.598
<i>of the swamp...</i>

14:10.757 --> 14:13.101
<i>- GARY: So we'll give it a go, mate?
- RICK: Okay.</i>

14:13.185 --> 14:16.512
<i>NARRATOR: Rick Lagina and
metal detection expert Gary Drayton</i>

14:16.597 --> 14:19.774
<i>arrive at the uplands on Lot 15.</i>

14:19.933 --> 14:22.026
<i>It was in this area...</i>

14:22.111 --> 14:23.185
What is this?

14:23.279 --> 14:24.696
<i>where just one week ago,</i>

14:24.780 --> 14:28.867
<i>Gary and Peter Fornetti
discovered an unusual iron band</i>

14:28.951 --> 14:31.452
<i>on nearby Lot 17,</i>

14:31.612 --> 14:35.281
<i>which once belonged to the wheel
of an old cart or wagon.</i>

14:35.365 --> 14:37.283
<i>This find not only dated</i>

14:37.376 --> 14:41.287
<i>to before the discovery
of the Money Pit in 1795,</i>

14:41.371 --> 14:44.457
<i>but also offered evidence
of a potential pathway</i>

14:44.550 --> 14:47.719
<i>between the swamp
and the original treasure shaft.</i>

14:47.803 --> 14:51.631
<i>To find this hidden road,
it is Rick and Gary's hope</i>

14:51.724 --> 14:54.142
<i>that uncovering a trail
of pre-searcher artifacts</i>

14:54.301 --> 14:56.728
<i>between Lot 15 and the Money Pit</i>

14:56.887 --> 14:59.397
<i>could prove this theory
to be true.</i>

14:59.481 --> 15:02.483
We put flags on any target

15:02.643 --> 15:04.068
that sounds good to me.

15:04.153 --> 15:06.562
- Mm-hmm.
- And now we've got permission to dig them up.

15:06.647 --> 15:08.656
So all we got to do is see
what they are,

15:08.741 --> 15:10.575
put them in a bag, mark them,

15:10.659 --> 15:13.903
exact same as the flag,
and Bob's your uncle.

15:13.987 --> 15:16.164
- Okay.
- Find something good.

15:16.248 --> 15:19.250
<i>RICK: Metal detecting is different
this year-- we have to create</i>

15:19.335 --> 15:21.336
transects, or grids,
across the island.

15:21.420 --> 15:24.672
Uh, we also have to get a permit

15:24.757 --> 15:26.749
<i>from Communities,
Culture and Heritage</i>

15:26.833 --> 15:29.427
<i>for that process to continue.</i>

15:30.671 --> 15:32.847
In that area there, mate.

15:33.006 --> 15:34.757
<i>NARRATOR:
In 2010,</i>

15:34.841 --> 15:37.352
<i>Rick, Marty,
Craig and their partners</i>

15:37.436 --> 15:40.262
<i>obtained permission from
the government of Nova Scotia</i>

15:40.347 --> 15:43.349
<i>to search for treasure
on Oak Island.</i>

15:43.433 --> 15:45.851
<i>It is the only location
within the province</i>

15:45.936 --> 15:48.020
<i>where such activities are legal.</i>

15:48.105 --> 15:51.282
<i>At the time, other than
the late 18th century homesteads</i>

15:51.367 --> 15:54.953
<i>that once belonged
to Samuel Ball-- on Lot 25--</i>

15:55.037 --> 15:58.289
<i>And Daniel McGinnis--
On Lot 21--</i>

15:58.448 --> 16:01.117
<i>They were subject
to few restrictions</i>

16:01.201 --> 16:02.368
<i>regarding
metal detecting activities</i>

16:02.452 --> 16:03.878
<i>across their property.</i>

16:04.037 --> 16:07.632
<i>That all changed in the wake
of the historic discoveries</i>

16:07.791 --> 16:09.875
<i>the team made last year
in the swamp,</i>

16:09.960 --> 16:12.053
<i>such as the massive stone road</i>

16:12.137 --> 16:14.630
<i>and the cobblestone pathway,</i>

16:14.715 --> 16:18.059
<i>which may be leading
in this direction on Lot 15,</i>

16:18.218 --> 16:21.721
<i>and potentially even toward
the original Money Pit.</i>

16:21.805 --> 16:26.401
I think the arising awareness
in the public

16:26.485 --> 16:28.394
of how important this might be

16:28.487 --> 16:32.073
has caused regulators
to sit up and pay attention,

16:32.232 --> 16:35.827
<i>in large part due to the success
of us making this real.</i>

16:36.996 --> 16:39.572
<i>NARRATOR: Now, other
than a designated green zone,</i>

16:39.656 --> 16:41.249
<i>which covers the Money Pit area</i>

16:41.333 --> 16:44.919
<i>from Lot 18
to Smith's Cove on Lot 20,</i>

16:45.004 --> 16:48.080
<i>Gary must first mark
metal targets that he detects</i>

16:48.165 --> 16:51.259
<i>with flags,
and then obtain permission</i>

16:51.418 --> 16:52.668
<i>from archaeologist Laird Niven</i>

16:52.761 --> 16:56.681
<i>to go back and retrieve
whatever they may be.</i>

16:57.850 --> 17:00.176
GARY:
There, mate.

17:00.260 --> 17:02.645
(beeping)

17:03.772 --> 17:05.765
GARY:
Oh!

17:05.849 --> 17:08.484
- Our old friend, the pull tab.
- Imagine that.

17:09.695 --> 17:12.280
Bag it and tag it,
even though it's trash.

17:12.439 --> 17:15.283
Yeah, I think issues like this
need to be addressed with CCH.

17:15.367 --> 17:17.610
This just seems like
a waste of time

17:17.703 --> 17:19.370
- and assets.
- Yeah.

17:19.529 --> 17:22.457
We have to really dig
through the trash

17:22.541 --> 17:24.709
to get to the treasures.

17:26.295 --> 17:30.039
<i>RICK: My hope is that the
positive will outweigh the negative,</i>

17:30.123 --> 17:33.718
but to be honest,
it will slow down the work.

17:33.877 --> 17:36.888
Yeah, it's like a scrapyard
around here.

17:36.972 --> 17:38.723
All right,
next flag is just here.

17:41.384 --> 17:43.227
(beeping)

17:43.312 --> 17:44.729
Just here.

17:58.077 --> 17:59.151
(beeping accelerates)

17:59.244 --> 18:01.746
That sounds even better.

18:07.577 --> 18:09.378
Whoa, look at that!

18:14.593 --> 18:15.167
There you go.

18:15.260 --> 18:16.177
It was there.

18:16.261 --> 18:17.261
Yeah!

18:17.420 --> 18:19.505
Ox shoe.

18:19.589 --> 18:23.342
<i>NARRATOR: On Lot 15, between
the swamp and the Money Pit,</i>

18:23.435 --> 18:27.021
<i>Rick Lagina and metal detection
expert Gary Drayton</i>

18:27.180 --> 18:30.024
<i>may have just discovered
what could be an important clue.</i>

18:30.183 --> 18:32.017
That looks like an oldie.

18:32.111 --> 18:33.528
Crazy, isn't it?

18:33.612 --> 18:36.605
So, all that modern junk,
and then we get

18:36.698 --> 18:39.283
an older ox shoe in this area.

18:39.368 --> 18:41.944
We're not too far off
the Money Pit, as well.

18:42.028 --> 18:44.029
And we found all those ox shoes

18:44.123 --> 18:46.874
- down below the so-called pine tar kiln.
- Yeah.

18:46.959 --> 18:49.618
<i>NARRATOR:
An ox shoe?</i>

18:49.703 --> 18:51.620
<i>Since the team has found
a number of ox shoes</i>

18:51.705 --> 18:54.039
<i>over the last year
on the island,</i>

18:54.133 --> 18:56.625
<i>might it be more evidence of,
not just a path</i>

18:56.710 --> 18:59.137
<i>between the swamp
and the Money Pit,</i>

18:59.221 --> 19:01.806
<i>but also an operation
to haul heavy cargo</i>

19:01.890 --> 19:04.466
<i>between the two locations,
as well?</i>

19:04.551 --> 19:06.218
That's cool.

19:06.311 --> 19:08.312
That's what we want
to be finding, some old stuff.

19:08.397 --> 19:10.898
And I knew there had to be
some more old stuff in here.

19:10.983 --> 19:12.316
It's just clearing all this out.

19:12.401 --> 19:14.643
And unfortunately,
somewhere like this,

19:14.728 --> 19:16.571
we're gonna have to take
all the surface junk out

19:16.730 --> 19:18.573
to get to the good stuff.

19:18.657 --> 19:20.825
<i>GARY:
Where you find ox shoes,</i>

19:20.909 --> 19:24.662
you're in an area which could
potentially be a trail,

19:24.746 --> 19:28.332
<i>or an area where treasure
was hauled, perhaps.</i>

19:28.491 --> 19:29.992
So...

19:30.076 --> 19:31.994
this is exciting.

19:32.087 --> 19:33.579
What is that? French? British?

19:33.663 --> 19:37.166
To me, it looks British, because
it's got that wider bottom...

19:37.259 --> 19:39.677
- Mm-hmm.
- And that thinner top.

19:39.761 --> 19:44.182
<i>NARRATOR: If Gary's assessment
about this ox shoe's origin is correct,</i>

19:44.341 --> 19:46.008
<i>could that mean
it may be connected</i>

19:46.101 --> 19:47.843
<i>to the British pine tar kiln</i>

19:47.928 --> 19:51.931
<i>that the team found
on Lot 15 last year?</i>

19:52.024 --> 19:54.692
<i>The same one that
archaeologist David McGinnis</i>

19:54.776 --> 19:58.687
<i>believes to date back
as far as the 16th century,</i>

19:58.772 --> 20:01.273
<i>and which Laird Niven suspects
may have been used</i>

20:01.366 --> 20:04.276
<i>in the construction
of the original Money Pit?</i>

20:04.361 --> 20:06.695
Maybe we should go back
to the old aerials.

20:06.780 --> 20:09.624
Plot this, these finds,
against the old aerials

20:09.708 --> 20:11.459
where it's cleared

20:11.543 --> 20:13.544
- Yeah.
- And see if they correspond.

20:13.703 --> 20:15.129
Yeah.

20:15.214 --> 20:17.548
Well, that's good.

20:17.633 --> 20:19.875
We know someone was here

20:19.960 --> 20:22.962
using an ox a long time ago.

20:23.046 --> 20:25.306
That's better, mate.
These are the type of finds

20:25.465 --> 20:27.058
we want to be recovering.

20:27.142 --> 20:29.852
I knew we could sniff out
an old find.

20:30.887 --> 20:34.023
<i>- On to the next flag.
- Okay.</i>

20:35.150 --> 20:37.818
<i>NARRATOR:
Later that afternoon...</i>

20:37.903 --> 20:41.572
<i>after being informed
of the mysterious piece of metal</i>

20:41.657 --> 20:44.650
<i>that was found in borehole D-2
in the Money Pit area...</i>

20:44.743 --> 20:45.660
All right, chaps.

20:45.744 --> 20:46.994
- How's it going?
- Good.

20:47.153 --> 20:50.081
<i>Rick Lagina, Gary Drayton
and Billy Gerhardt</i>

20:50.165 --> 20:53.834
<i>join geoscientist
Dr. Ian Spooner and Laird Niven</i>

20:53.919 --> 20:56.662
<i>in the archaeology trailer.</i>

20:56.755 --> 20:59.665
<i>In order to learn
what the object is composed of,</i>

20:59.749 --> 21:02.668
<i>they are preparing to scan it
using an XRF,</i>

21:02.752 --> 21:05.254
<i>or X-Ray Fluorescence device.</i>

21:05.338 --> 21:07.589
RICK: I believe the
classroom is now full.

21:07.674 --> 21:09.267
- (chuckles)
- Excellent.

21:09.351 --> 21:11.343
So, I want to show you

21:11.428 --> 21:13.012
a piece of metal that came up.

21:13.105 --> 21:14.188
I think it's D-2,

21:14.273 --> 21:17.182
uh, near C-1 at 88 feet.

21:17.267 --> 21:19.268
So, it's
a very interesting zone,

21:19.352 --> 21:21.028
and it's really odd,
to me at least,

21:21.187 --> 21:22.855
that metal's coming up.

21:22.939 --> 21:24.189
- Did wood come up with it?
- Yeah.

21:24.283 --> 21:25.533
Wood came up.

21:25.692 --> 21:29.287
So, I'm just gonna throw it on
and see what we get.

21:31.873 --> 21:34.542
- This should be interesting.
- Yeah.

21:34.701 --> 21:36.785
Let's just give it a shot here.

21:36.878 --> 21:39.714
<i>RICK: When I learned that
they had found some metals,</i>

21:39.798 --> 21:42.624
<i>at depth,
I'm there in a heartbeat.</i>

21:42.709 --> 21:45.052
Wow. Those are
some strange elements.

21:45.137 --> 21:46.378
- Right.
- Yeah.

21:46.471 --> 21:47.888
<i>This horizon,</i>

21:47.973 --> 21:50.382
to me, it's very interesting.

21:50.467 --> 21:52.310
The tunnels that
have been found previously,

21:52.394 --> 21:55.054
whether they were inferred
to be original work

21:55.138 --> 21:57.732
or part of the searcher work,

21:57.891 --> 21:59.233
<i>was previously unknown.</i>

21:59.318 --> 22:01.143
<i>And the addition of the XRF</i>

22:01.227 --> 22:03.321
<i>has been a boon to understanding</i>

22:03.405 --> 22:05.564
<i>the importance
of some of these artifacts.</i>

22:05.648 --> 22:09.493
Osmium. Is that cobalt? Iridium.

22:09.578 --> 22:10.995
Manganese.

22:11.154 --> 22:13.655
- Zirconium?
- IAN: Zirconium, that's correct.

22:13.740 --> 22:15.240
Titanium.

22:15.334 --> 22:16.584
GARY:
AU!

22:16.668 --> 22:18.660
RICK:
Really?

22:18.745 --> 22:19.670
IAN: Well, let's
just let it figure out...

22:19.755 --> 22:21.747
It's doing all its math
right now.

22:21.831 --> 22:23.841
That would be gold.

22:24.000 --> 22:25.676
- I don't see that yet, Gary.
- No, I did.

22:25.761 --> 22:28.003
- I saw it flash. Yeah, I did.
- BILLY: It flashed for a second.

22:28.088 --> 22:29.764
- I saw that AU.
- Let's move it around a bit,

22:29.923 --> 22:31.173
'cause I saw that, too.

22:31.266 --> 22:33.258
<i>NARRATOR:
Traces of gold?</i>

22:33.343 --> 22:35.353
<i>Detected on the mysterious piece
of metal</i>

22:35.512 --> 22:38.097
<i>retrieved from D-2
in the Money Pit?</i>

22:38.181 --> 22:41.359
<i>Could it mean that the team
is close to pinpointing</i>

22:41.443 --> 22:44.362
<i>the location of the fabled
Oak Island treasure?</i>

22:46.773 --> 22:49.533
- GARY: There it is! AU!
- RICK: There it is.

22:51.787 --> 22:53.120
IAN:
That's-that's pretty high.

22:53.279 --> 22:56.874
Like, 6-8? Yeah, .068%.

22:56.958 --> 22:59.368
Not parts per million,
but percent.

22:59.452 --> 23:00.702
Is that a large amount of gold?

23:00.796 --> 23:02.871
Yeah, that's more gold
than you think.

23:02.956 --> 23:06.300
Like a dump truck full of gold?

23:06.385 --> 23:08.052
(chuckles):
No. That amount is...

23:08.136 --> 23:11.630
No, a thimble.
A thimble full of gold.

23:11.714 --> 23:14.475
I think we were all shocked
that there was a gold signature

23:14.559 --> 23:16.811
<i>when they ran the XRF
on these metals.</i>

23:16.895 --> 23:18.554
Well, I love this machine now.

23:18.638 --> 23:19.980
(laughs): Yeah. We've
had this thing for a year,

23:20.065 --> 23:21.816
and I've done a fair bit
of metal on it

23:21.900 --> 23:23.901
and I've never seen any gold.

23:25.895 --> 23:27.154
<i>RICK: I don't know
what to make of it.</i>

23:27.239 --> 23:28.823
<i>Follow the science.</i>

23:28.907 --> 23:32.076
Is it possibly an aha moment?
Yes, it is.

23:33.078 --> 23:34.912
IAN:
So it's significant gold.

23:35.071 --> 23:37.322
It's either on the surface
of the metal,

23:37.416 --> 23:38.574
or it's on...

23:38.658 --> 23:41.660
the sediment on the metal,

23:41.744 --> 23:43.671
'cause it hasn't been cleaned.

23:43.755 --> 23:46.915
GARY: Does this, in your
opinion, make it more likely

23:47.000 --> 23:49.918
that there is treasure
in the Money Pit?

23:50.003 --> 23:54.515
Well, there's gold on the metal
at 88 to 92 feet,

23:54.674 --> 23:55.850
somewhere around there.

23:55.934 --> 23:58.269
I mean,
it's not what I expected.

23:58.353 --> 23:59.770
I've got one piece
of a big puzzle.

23:59.855 --> 24:04.108
The water's another piece.
And these data are coming in.

24:04.267 --> 24:06.518
They're provocative
in exactly the spot

24:06.611 --> 24:10.355
that you'd expect provocative
results to come from.

24:10.440 --> 24:15.360
So, I'm getting surprised
at a furious rate these days.

24:15.454 --> 24:16.370
(laughter)

24:16.455 --> 24:19.198
- Welcome to the island.
- Yeah.

24:19.291 --> 24:21.700
RICK: It's just more homework,
more in-depth analysis,

24:21.793 --> 24:24.628
and I think in combination
with the water sampling,

24:24.713 --> 24:27.539
the lab work,

24:27.624 --> 24:30.634
as a team, we can move this
thing forward at this point.

24:30.793 --> 24:33.220
I think we're
on a very good path to success.

24:33.379 --> 24:35.130
- Yeah.
- Anyway...

24:35.215 --> 24:37.391
- We better go find some more.
- Yes.

24:37.476 --> 24:39.551
<i>GARY:
That was good news.</i>

24:39.636 --> 24:40.603
<i>BILLY:
Sure was.</i>

24:48.236 --> 24:50.905
<i>NARRATOR: One day after
unearthing a metal object</i>

24:51.064 --> 24:54.316
<i>which contains high traces
of gold from the Money Pit...</i>

24:54.400 --> 24:57.903
- 48.7 meters without casing.
- Yeah, 48.7.

24:57.987 --> 25:00.247
<i>the drilling operation there
continues</i>

25:00.332 --> 25:02.750
<i>in search
of more valuable clues.</i>

25:02.834 --> 25:04.335
STEVE G.:
We've got a long ways to go.

25:05.504 --> 25:07.162
<i>Meanwhile...</i>

25:07.247 --> 25:09.248
- Morning. - Morning.
- MIRIAM: Hi.

25:09.341 --> 25:10.841
We found rocks.

25:11.000 --> 25:13.260
- Yeah, you sure did.
- Yeah, we're just...

25:13.345 --> 25:14.836
we're just kind of
cleaning it off.

25:14.921 --> 25:16.088
<i>Rick Lagina</i>

25:16.181 --> 25:18.757
<i>and heavy equipment operator
Billy Gerhardt</i>

25:18.850 --> 25:21.343
<i>arrive at the southeastern
corner of the swamp,</i>

25:21.427 --> 25:24.846
<i>where archaeologists
Miriam Amirault and Laird Niven</i>

25:24.931 --> 25:27.683
<i>have just uncovered
what they believe to be</i>

25:27.767 --> 25:30.528
<i>more of the ancient stone
ship's wharf.</i>

25:30.612 --> 25:32.521
So, what's the plan
for the day, then?

25:32.605 --> 25:34.698
Um, if you don't mind
helping Miriam...

25:34.857 --> 25:36.608
I will... I will do
whatever you tell me.

25:36.693 --> 25:38.443
- I'll work with Billy.
- Yep.

25:38.537 --> 25:40.371
- And we'll start.
- Then we'll go in here. - All right.

25:45.961 --> 25:47.294
<i>RICK:
It's an ongoing story,</i>

25:47.379 --> 25:48.629
<i>and that's what
the archaeologists</i>

25:48.788 --> 25:50.038
<i>have really taught us.</i>

25:50.131 --> 25:53.041
You're not gonna find one or two
or five or ten things

25:53.126 --> 25:55.052
and go, "There's the story."

25:56.129 --> 25:59.640
<i>This is evolving, and I'm glad</i>

25:59.799 --> 26:03.051
<i>that they're leading the charge.</i>

26:03.136 --> 26:07.889
Rick, will you just grab that...
those couple sticks?

26:07.974 --> 26:09.692
I don't know
if they're important or not.

26:16.649 --> 26:18.650
- That's interesting.
- That's a different one.

26:18.735 --> 26:20.369
Miriam?

26:23.248 --> 26:25.824
- What's up?
- Look.

26:25.908 --> 26:28.168
Well, that's weird.

26:28.253 --> 26:30.495
I've never seen
anything like that.

26:30.589 --> 26:33.007
No. It's broken here.

26:33.091 --> 26:35.334
Almost like a bowl. Feel that.

26:35.427 --> 26:37.753
It's concave.

26:37.837 --> 26:39.597
Oh!

26:39.681 --> 26:41.932
Oh, that's really weird.

26:42.091 --> 26:44.685
Laird? Do you want to come here
for a second?

26:44.844 --> 26:46.428
LAIRD:
What do you have?

26:46.512 --> 26:48.013
- Hey. - I don't know.
- Oh.

26:48.097 --> 26:49.607
What is it?

26:54.771 --> 26:56.614
- No idea, Laird?
- No.

26:56.698 --> 26:59.191
I don't. I really don't.

26:59.275 --> 27:02.202
But given the items that we
think are associated with boats

27:02.287 --> 27:07.115
or building of boats, this might
be a maritime object as well.

27:07.200 --> 27:08.792
Makes sense.

27:08.951 --> 27:10.544
Yep.

27:10.703 --> 27:12.371
<i>NARRATOR:
It was the belief</i>

27:12.464 --> 27:14.956
<i>of the late Oak Island
treasure hunter Fred Nolan</i>

27:15.041 --> 27:17.718
<i>that the swamp
had been artificially created</i>

27:17.877 --> 27:21.305
<i>in order to hide the wreck
of a massive treasure galleon.</i>

27:21.389 --> 27:27.227
<i>In 2019, Rick, Marty,
Craig and the team identified</i>

27:27.312 --> 27:30.147
<i>a mysterious 200-foot-long,
galleon-shaped anomaly</i>

27:30.306 --> 27:32.224
<i>deep in the middle
of the brackish bog</i>

27:32.308 --> 27:34.151
<i>using seismic scanning.</i>

27:34.310 --> 27:37.237
<i>However,
that was only the beginning.</i>

27:37.322 --> 27:40.658
- Oh, yeah.
- Oh, look at that! That's nice!

27:40.742 --> 27:43.652
That is old.
It's a handmade spike.

27:43.736 --> 27:47.239
<i>They have also found
17th century ship spikes...</i>

27:47.332 --> 27:50.334
- MARTY: What is that?
<i>- Possible deck planking...</i>

27:50.418 --> 27:52.252
<i>and a number
of burned wood pieces</i>

27:52.412 --> 27:56.748
<i>that blacksmith Carmen Legge
believes to be parts of a ship.</i>

27:56.833 --> 27:59.593
It's almost like it's meant
to rest on something

27:59.678 --> 28:00.919
or go into something.

28:01.003 --> 28:04.181
<i>Now, after finding
another wooden artifact</i>

28:04.265 --> 28:06.007
<i>next to the ancient stone
ship's wharf</i>

28:06.101 --> 28:08.343
<i>in the swamp's
southeastern corner,</i>

28:08.436 --> 28:11.012
<i>could the team
be close to proving</i>

28:11.097 --> 28:13.107
<i>that Fred Nolan was right?</i>

28:13.191 --> 28:14.191
It's really cool.

28:14.350 --> 28:15.693
I've never seen
anything like that.

28:15.777 --> 28:17.695
- RICK: Somebody will know.
- LAIRD: Somebody will know.

28:17.854 --> 28:19.196
Okay,

28:19.280 --> 28:20.948
<i>- I'll take care of it.
- All righty.</i>

28:21.107 --> 28:23.033
<i>LAIRD:
All right.</i>

28:23.118 --> 28:26.778
<i>NARRATOR:
Later that afternoon...</i>

28:26.863 --> 28:29.123
<i>while drilling continues
in the Money Pit...</i>

28:29.207 --> 28:32.459
Oh, yeah, right to the bottom.

28:32.544 --> 28:35.871
<i>GARY: I was looking forward
to coming back in this area.</i>

28:35.955 --> 28:39.466
<i>Rick Lagina and Gary Drayton
arrive on Lot 16</i>

28:39.551 --> 28:42.386
<i>to continue searching for clues
along the possible pathway</i>

28:42.545 --> 28:45.889
<i>between the swamp
and the Money Pit.</i>

28:46.891 --> 28:48.308
We've got to find
something good.

28:48.468 --> 28:49.351
Let's find something good.

28:50.553 --> 28:54.222
I have my favorite shovel,
if that helps.

28:54.307 --> 28:56.391
GARY: Your favorite
shovel and my lucky digger--

28:56.484 --> 28:58.902
- What can go wrong?
- (laughs)

29:04.066 --> 29:05.576
It's probably in the top.

29:05.735 --> 29:09.079
I expect some junk here, 'cause
we're not too far off the lane.

29:09.238 --> 29:10.071
Sure.

29:10.165 --> 29:12.824
Let's see
if I can pinpoint for...

29:12.909 --> 29:14.752
(beeping)

29:16.254 --> 29:17.755
-(rapid beeping) -There
you go. Yeah, we're on it.

29:20.249 --> 29:22.760
A square nail,
by the look of it.

29:22.919 --> 29:24.762
A big chunky one.
Yeah, it's tough to say

29:24.846 --> 29:27.589
how old it is,
but, I mean, it's heavy.

29:27.682 --> 29:29.174
- Mm-hmm.
- I know it's an oldie.

29:29.258 --> 29:31.510
That's maybe the head
of the nail. I don't know.

29:31.603 --> 29:34.354
Yeah, 'cause that tells
the story of the nail, the head.

29:34.439 --> 29:35.597
Well, mate, great start.

29:35.681 --> 29:37.599
- I'll tag and bag it.
- Okay.

29:37.683 --> 29:40.944
<i>RICK: The hope is that you
can connect these artifacts</i>

29:41.029 --> 29:44.281
<i>with other artifacts
that have been found.</i>

29:44.365 --> 29:45.949
Because there's always someone
who knows something

29:46.034 --> 29:49.203
about the most esoteric subject,
maybe there's someone

29:49.362 --> 29:51.371
who can look at all the spikes
and say: You know what, guys?

29:51.456 --> 29:53.624
There's
a cultural influence here.

29:53.708 --> 29:56.701
Or maybe there's
a specific forging technique.

29:56.786 --> 29:58.879
They are not just static finds.

29:58.963 --> 30:01.790
They should be able
to tell us something.

30:01.874 --> 30:04.960
One thing I've noticed
when we flagged this area,

30:05.044 --> 30:08.213
Peter and I,
is that most of the targets

30:08.306 --> 30:11.883
seem to be along the top here
and along the bottom.

30:11.976 --> 30:14.052
So the next group of targets
are down near the water.

30:14.136 --> 30:15.312
Okay.

30:23.488 --> 30:24.729
<i>GARY:
Hold it!</i>

30:24.814 --> 30:26.147
<i>- Do you see what I see?
- RICK: Oh, yeah.</i>

30:26.232 --> 30:27.983
<i>NARRATOR:
On Lot 16,</i>

30:28.067 --> 30:29.910
<i>between the swamp
and the Money Pit,</i>

30:29.994 --> 30:32.162
<i>Gary Drayton and Rick Lagina</i>

30:32.247 --> 30:34.832
<i>have just made what could be
an important discovery.</i>

30:34.916 --> 30:37.909
Look at the shape of that.

30:37.994 --> 30:40.420
Whoa, look at that!

30:40.505 --> 30:42.247
It's a round shot!

30:42.340 --> 30:44.424
RICK:
Wow.

30:44.584 --> 30:46.343
Dang, that is a nice find.

30:48.012 --> 30:50.764
<i>NARRATOR:
A piece of round shot?</i>

30:50.923 --> 30:55.185
<i>Although dating as far back
as the 12th century in China,</i>

30:55.344 --> 30:57.762
<i>round shot is
a spherical projectile</i>

30:57.847 --> 30:59.014
<i>designed to be launched</i>

30:59.098 --> 31:02.776
<i>from both cannons
and handheld firearms.</i>

31:02.861 --> 31:04.936
<i>While the early form
of round shot</i>

31:05.021 --> 31:07.272
<i>was made of stone,
it was eventually replaced</i>

31:07.365 --> 31:11.034
<i>by iron throughout Europe
in the 17th century.</i>

31:12.695 --> 31:14.705
Steve, look at this.

31:14.864 --> 31:15.956
Oh, wow.

31:16.040 --> 31:18.292
<i>Last year,
while sifting through the spoils</i>

31:18.376 --> 31:20.952
<i>excavated
from the Money Pit area,</i>

31:21.037 --> 31:23.380
<i>treasure hunter
Michael John discovered</i>

31:23.464 --> 31:26.884
<i>a very similar small,
round stone.</i>

31:26.968 --> 31:28.802
- Have you seen this, Gary?
- This...

31:28.887 --> 31:31.880
is a dress stone,
or a gun stone.

31:31.964 --> 31:34.892
This is really, really old.

31:34.976 --> 31:38.061
Before the days of cannonballs,
iron cannonballs.

31:39.639 --> 31:41.899
<i>Could this piece of stone shot,</i>

31:41.983 --> 31:44.484
<i>found between the swamp
and the Money Pit,</i>

31:44.644 --> 31:47.896
<i>and the one found last year
in the Money Pit area itself</i>

31:47.980 --> 31:49.406
<i>be connected?</i>

31:49.490 --> 31:53.076
This being stone shot, mate,
wonder where this came from.

31:53.161 --> 31:55.579
You'd have to say it came
from the water,

31:55.663 --> 31:57.998
- Yeah.
- Which is not too far away.

31:58.157 --> 32:02.002
And about the right distance if
you was firing a small cannon.

32:02.086 --> 32:04.087
So how big a cannon
does that come out of?

32:04.246 --> 32:06.164
It would... more than likely,
it would have been

32:06.257 --> 32:07.925
like a small rail gun,

32:08.009 --> 32:09.259
- Mm-hmm.
- That would have been attached

32:09.344 --> 32:11.261
to the side of the boat,

32:11.420 --> 32:15.766
and this would have been
an antipersonnel ammo.

32:15.850 --> 32:18.009
It would have been
like scattershot.

32:18.094 --> 32:19.603
It would be interesting

32:19.762 --> 32:21.104
just to bring, like,
a rototiller up here

32:21.189 --> 32:24.683
- and see if there's more of them.
- Yeah, we really should.

32:24.776 --> 32:26.935
I thought it was a bird's egg
when I first saw it.

32:27.028 --> 32:28.937
Well, that
just goes to show, mate,

32:29.030 --> 32:30.855
using your twin
optical scanners.

32:30.949 --> 32:32.366
RICK: Oh, yeah, it's
an amazing surface find.

32:32.450 --> 32:34.192
Rarely do we find those.

32:34.276 --> 32:36.954
GARY:
Oh, without a doubt.

32:42.043 --> 32:44.795
<i>NARRATOR:
The following morning...</i>

32:44.879 --> 32:48.790
MARTY: We're back,
Oak Island, old friend.

32:48.874 --> 32:50.959
- Okay, well, how you feeling, Alex?
- Good.

32:51.043 --> 32:54.129
<i>Rick Lagina has just picked up
his brother Marty</i>

32:54.213 --> 32:57.057
<i>and nephew Alex after their trip
from Traverse City, Michigan,</i>

32:57.216 --> 32:59.726
<i>to Halifax, Nova Scotia.</i>

32:59.885 --> 33:01.478
Yeah, I'm glad to be back.

33:01.637 --> 33:03.304
Looking at this from afar,
and, you know,

33:03.389 --> 33:05.148
- Mm-hmm. Yep, yep.
- Punching in and punching out.

33:05.233 --> 33:06.483
What do you find
the most exciting?

33:06.567 --> 33:08.485
What is the things that
you're dying to show us

33:08.569 --> 33:11.312
and that, you know, I mean,
we can sink our teeth into?

33:11.397 --> 33:14.324
I might as well show it to you
right now.

33:14.409 --> 33:17.160
This is the most curious thing
of all.

33:19.664 --> 33:20.739
What is that?

33:20.823 --> 33:22.165
RICK:
That's one of the pieces

33:22.324 --> 33:26.911
of metal we retrieved
from D-2 up by C-1.

33:26.996 --> 33:28.830
There's a gold signature
on that.

33:28.914 --> 33:30.749
Really?

33:30.833 --> 33:33.251
Per the XRF?

33:33.344 --> 33:35.170
- Yep.
- This...

33:35.254 --> 33:37.431
is probably
the most exciting thing

33:37.515 --> 33:40.008
- Yeah.
- In terms of a treasure hunt.

33:40.101 --> 33:41.342
- Yes.
- Not the information hunt,

33:41.436 --> 33:43.094
- but the treasure hunt.
- Yes.

33:43.187 --> 33:45.430
- Yeah.
- RICK: The other curious thing about that

33:45.514 --> 33:48.933
is that it's right in the
horizon of one of the tunnels,

33:49.018 --> 33:52.279
- Mm-hmm.
- the 86 to 93 tunnels up around C-1.

33:52.363 --> 33:54.439
This was found at 88 and a half.

33:54.523 --> 33:56.608
And that's a much more
plausible depth than 220.

33:56.701 --> 33:57.942
MARTY:
Exactly.

33:58.027 --> 33:59.536
Exactly.

33:59.695 --> 34:01.371
Well, that kind of brings us
up to speed,

34:01.456 --> 34:04.365
but our first task here, though,
when we get there

34:04.459 --> 34:05.950
is to get in
the war room, right?

34:06.044 --> 34:09.129
'Cause Craig's here, and Craig
has some, to my understanding,

34:09.213 --> 34:11.289
more C-14 data, is that right?

34:11.373 --> 34:15.469
Yep, and I'm gathering that
it's gonna be very interesting.

34:15.553 --> 34:18.722
And it's in the D-2 borehole.

34:18.806 --> 34:20.223
Well, that's the same one.

34:20.382 --> 34:21.808
- The same one, yes.
- As this stuff.

34:21.893 --> 34:23.310
- With the gold.
- Yes. Yes.

34:23.469 --> 34:24.219
<i>MARTY:
All right.</i>

34:24.312 --> 34:25.804
<i>We had silver in the water,</i>

34:25.888 --> 34:27.731
<i>we had gold in the water,
now we're seeing gold</i>

34:27.890 --> 34:30.558
<i>on a piece of metal unearthed...</i>

34:30.651 --> 34:32.486
<i>in the Money Pit at a depth</i>

34:32.570 --> 34:34.321
<i>where an offset chamber
might lie.</i>

34:34.405 --> 34:36.064
<i>That is really encouraging.</i>

34:36.148 --> 34:38.241
<i>It's the first direct evidence</i>

34:38.326 --> 34:41.069
<i>that precious metals
might be here.</i>

34:41.153 --> 34:42.821
I'd say we're closing in
on the treasure.

34:42.905 --> 34:44.572
MARTY:
Gentlemen!

34:44.657 --> 34:46.241
- We're back!
- Welcome!

34:46.325 --> 34:47.575
SCOTT:
Welcome to Oak Island.

34:47.660 --> 34:49.669
Good to see you all.
Good to be back.

34:49.829 --> 34:51.246
I hope you feel the same.

34:51.330 --> 34:52.506
(laughter)

34:52.590 --> 34:53.665
DOUG:
Absolutely.

34:53.758 --> 34:56.426
Anyway, we're here.
Good to see you all.

34:56.511 --> 34:58.178
What the hell
you got here, Craig?

34:58.262 --> 35:01.005
- Samples.
- Do you got a bunch of new data for us?

35:01.099 --> 35:03.758
Uh, just one new data,
but I wanted to incorporate

35:03.843 --> 35:06.761
some of the old finds
we found in here, too.

35:06.846 --> 35:08.930
MARTY:
Okay.

35:09.014 --> 35:11.099
This is, uh, the other one,
this is from last year.

35:11.183 --> 35:14.686
This is CD-2.5,

35:14.779 --> 35:18.281
which is only a few feet away
from... from this one.

35:18.366 --> 35:21.785
And this is
from 91 and a half feet,

35:21.944 --> 35:23.954
so just, you know,
a foot and a half deeper.

35:24.038 --> 35:26.531
- Really?
- 1488 to 1650.

35:26.624 --> 35:28.449
Just one period.

35:28.534 --> 35:30.043
It's certainly...

35:30.128 --> 35:32.462
I mean, it's inarguable.

35:32.547 --> 35:34.047
We need to put a caisson
at this location.

35:34.132 --> 35:36.633
- GARY: Yep.
- CRAIG: And then,

35:36.717 --> 35:39.302
everybody knows D-2, kind of
an exciting well this year.

35:39.387 --> 35:42.046
We brought up
the pieces of metal,

35:42.140 --> 35:45.049
brought up wood
all around the 90-foot level.

35:45.134 --> 35:46.384
Wait a second,
you mean the piece of metal

35:46.468 --> 35:48.386
- with gold on it, that one?
- The piece of metal

35:48.470 --> 35:49.813
- with gold on it, exactly.
- Okay.

35:49.897 --> 35:50.981
Just wanted to be able
to say that.

35:51.065 --> 35:52.315
(laughter)

35:54.226 --> 35:55.643
CRAIG:
And, uh, so, you know,

35:55.728 --> 35:58.989
one thing we did was, we sent
the wood out for testing,

35:59.148 --> 36:02.242
and this is the sample
from 90-foot,

36:02.326 --> 36:06.321
and, uh, it came back
from Beta Analytical

36:06.405 --> 36:08.498
- with one time period.
- That's good.

36:08.583 --> 36:11.334
1488 to 1650.

36:11.419 --> 36:12.577
- Really and truthfully?
- CRAIG: Yeah. - GARY: Wow!

36:12.670 --> 36:14.087
ALEX:
Wow.

36:14.246 --> 36:15.830
Exact same time period.

36:15.923 --> 36:18.416
- ALEX: Wow.
- Pre-Columbian date.

36:18.500 --> 36:21.669
I find that incredibly amazing.

36:21.762 --> 36:23.513
<i>GARY:
That is incredible.</i>

36:27.351 --> 36:29.010
<i>NARRATOR:
In the Oak Island war room,</i>

36:29.094 --> 36:31.679
<i>Craig Tester has just presented
an astonishing scientific report</i>

36:31.764 --> 36:33.857
<i>regarding wood that was obtained</i>

36:33.941 --> 36:37.936
<i>just two days ago from
borehole D-2 in the Money Pit.</i>

36:38.029 --> 36:39.687
That's crazy.

36:39.780 --> 36:41.856
- Wow.
- GARY: That is incredible.

36:41.949 --> 36:46.027
<i>NARRATOR: Matching a sample
taken last year from borehole CD-2.5,</i>

36:46.111 --> 36:48.955
<i>which sat just two feet away,
the wood dates</i>

36:49.040 --> 36:51.950
<i>to as early
as the late 15th century,</i>

36:52.043 --> 36:54.035
<i>more than 300 years
before the discovery</i>

36:54.119 --> 36:56.955
<i>of the original Money Pit.</i>

36:57.039 --> 37:01.125
So, whether these are both
the same log...

37:01.219 --> 37:02.710
Wait, I want to revel in this
a little bit.

37:02.795 --> 37:04.387
(laughter)

37:04.472 --> 37:05.472
Seriously, this is very...

37:05.556 --> 37:08.058
We don't have
the oddball bracket here.

37:09.227 --> 37:11.394
ALEX:
Is that clearly warped wood?

37:11.553 --> 37:14.889
I mean, is it obviously
man-made and...

37:14.974 --> 37:18.151
Uh, yeah, this is stacked
upon each other, yeah.

37:18.236 --> 37:19.486
- To me, that's huge, don't you think?
- MARTY: Yeah,

37:19.645 --> 37:23.147
and the only other thing,
if it was a log and the...

37:23.241 --> 37:26.076
glacial stuff, it should be
10,000 years old, right?

37:26.160 --> 37:28.662
- Yeah.
- RICK: Historical data indicates

37:28.746 --> 37:32.249
to the north of C-1,
or even in C-1, was...

37:32.333 --> 37:33.908
unexplored, literally.

37:33.993 --> 37:36.661
And so now, yes, this data,

37:36.754 --> 37:40.173
- this... the metal pieces...
- Absolutely. - Right.

37:40.258 --> 37:41.841
These dates just support

37:42.001 --> 37:44.002
my belief for a long time

37:44.095 --> 37:46.754
that whatever work was done here
was done quite early.

37:46.839 --> 37:48.431
Exactly. Exactly.

37:49.767 --> 37:51.685
<i>NARRATOR: Because
of more than two centuries</i>

37:51.769 --> 37:54.938
<i>of prior searcher excavations
and subsequent cave-ins</i>

37:55.097 --> 37:57.440
<i>caused by the man-made
flood tunnels,</i>

37:57.525 --> 37:59.934
<i>the location
of the original Money Pit</i>

38:00.019 --> 38:03.354
<i>has been lost
since the early 1900s.</i>

38:03.439 --> 38:05.940
<i>Could the matching
carbon dating of the wood</i>

38:06.025 --> 38:08.618
<i>in borehole D-2 and CD-2.5</i>

38:08.777 --> 38:11.705
<i>mean that the team
has finally rediscovered</i>

38:11.789 --> 38:15.533
<i>the original treasure shaft?</i>

38:15.626 --> 38:18.211
So, it has always seemed
virtually impossible to me

38:18.296 --> 38:20.288
that after all the holes
we've put down

38:20.372 --> 38:22.299
in the conventional
Money Pit area,

38:22.458 --> 38:23.967
that this treasure
could still be hiding

38:24.126 --> 38:26.553
<i>in the conventional
Money Pit area.</i>

38:26.712 --> 38:29.797
This has 95.4% confident.

38:29.890 --> 38:32.892
<i>But I think
it's entirely more likely</i>

38:32.977 --> 38:34.469
that we've been looking
in the wrong place

38:34.562 --> 38:38.148
and that these new holes might
be where the real treasure is.

38:41.143 --> 38:45.146
To get those dates there, that's
pre-searcher by a long shot.

38:45.230 --> 38:47.815
The Templars
could have been here first.

38:47.900 --> 38:48.900
Medieval, baby!

38:48.984 --> 38:51.578
- There it is!
- I couldn't resist it.

38:51.737 --> 38:53.571
I wasn't going to leave
till I got one of those, Gary.

38:53.655 --> 38:54.914
RICK:
You know what?

38:54.999 --> 38:58.835
What this does say, as
definitive as these results are,

38:58.919 --> 39:01.496
if you try to...

39:01.589 --> 39:04.007
do a probability window, say,

39:04.166 --> 39:05.925
about the various theories,
they all fit.

39:06.085 --> 39:08.503
They pretty much do.

39:08.596 --> 39:11.923
<i>RICK: There are various
theories that seem to indicate</i>

39:12.007 --> 39:16.436
possible evolving of
the Templars into Rosicrucians,

39:16.520 --> 39:18.596
into Free Masonry,

39:18.680 --> 39:21.516
<i>and there's
so much fractured history there</i>

39:21.600 --> 39:23.860
<i>that it's very difficult to say
with clarity,</i>

39:23.944 --> 39:28.272
<i>"This-- aha!-- this is what
happened in this time period."</i>

39:28.357 --> 39:32.110
<i>But there is no denying that
this story has persisted</i>

39:32.194 --> 39:35.622
<i>because of the belief
that there is treasure</i>

39:35.706 --> 39:37.624
buried on Oak Island.

39:37.708 --> 39:39.700
I mean, think about it, right?

39:39.785 --> 39:43.129
14 years in,
down the road of discovery here,

39:43.214 --> 39:46.874
we thought surely science
will carry the day,

39:46.959 --> 39:49.552
and now it
certainly has paid dividends,

39:49.637 --> 39:52.138
but we also thought that,
one by one,

39:52.223 --> 39:53.798
we could eliminate this theory

39:53.882 --> 39:55.800
and that theory and this theory

39:55.893 --> 39:58.553
and get down, narrow it down
to one, two or three.

39:58.646 --> 40:01.231
And yet,
five or six still remain,

40:01.390 --> 40:04.401
even with specific information
like this.

40:04.560 --> 40:06.811
MARTY:
Well, I think we can eliminate

40:06.904 --> 40:10.573
or just about eliminate
one of the theories, Rick.

40:10.658 --> 40:12.992
The, uh,
"nothing happened" theory.

40:13.077 --> 40:14.986
- That's pretty much dead.
- I'd say that's a...

40:15.079 --> 40:17.155
- It's pretty much dying fast.
- It's dead and buried.

40:17.248 --> 40:19.833
So, with that thought,
let's all get back out there

40:19.992 --> 40:22.669
- and do what we're doing.
- Yep.

40:22.753 --> 40:26.256
<i>NARRATOR: With every search
operation that they conduct,</i>

40:26.340 --> 40:29.250
<i>and with every new technology
that they apply,</i>

40:29.334 --> 40:32.262
<i>Rick, Marty,
Craig and their team</i>

40:32.346 --> 40:35.765
<i>are collecting more pieces
of the Oak Island puzzle.</i>

40:35.924 --> 40:39.427
<i>But as the picture
continues to take shape,</i>

40:39.511 --> 40:41.938
<i>will they ultimately identify
a masterful group</i>

40:42.022 --> 40:46.359
<i>of conspirators who hid
something of great value here?</i>

40:46.444 --> 40:51.022
<i>Or several of them, who,
connected by a secret agenda,</i>

40:51.106 --> 40:55.368
<i>made numerous deposits
over a number of generations?</i>

40:55.453 --> 40:58.204
<i>What is almost certain
is that treasure</i>

40:58.363 --> 41:01.866
<i>still lies buried on Oak Island.</i>

41:01.959 --> 41:04.452
<i>The question is,</i>

41:04.536 --> 41:09.299
<i>can anything stop the Laginas
and their team from finding it?</i>

41:09.383 --> 41:11.468
(wind whistling)

41:11.627 --> 41:14.137
Next time
on<i> The Curse of Oak Island...</i>

41:14.296 --> 41:15.221
<i>MARTY:
If there really is gold found</i>

41:15.306 --> 41:17.724
<i>on these pieces of metal,
this is</i>

41:17.883 --> 41:18.641
very, very significant.

41:18.726 --> 41:20.727
Wow, this is really interesting.

41:20.811 --> 41:22.979
So, we have
ancient Spanish gold.

41:23.063 --> 41:24.305
- That's huge.
<i>- So, when you project</i>

41:24.389 --> 41:25.982
this path,
it heads to the Money Pit.

41:26.141 --> 41:27.484
Wow!

41:27.568 --> 41:30.144
<i>LAIRD: Department of
Community, Culture and Heritage</i>

41:30.229 --> 41:32.071
asked that we stop down
immediately.

41:32.231 --> 41:34.157
<i>It is very discouraging to me.</i>

41:34.241 --> 41:37.818
<i>The more we cooperate,
the more of our island we lose.</i>

41:37.903 --> 41:39.662
<i>Fine, let's throw in the towel.</i>

